tween a pair of nodes, we opt for simplicity and adopt a simple decoder based on multi-layer perceptron (MLP), given the representations of node pairs and their treatments. That is, the decoder g is deï¬ned as

A = g(Z, T), s.t. Ai,j = MLP([zi zj, Ti,j]),

(6)

ACF = g(Z, TCF ), s.t. ACi,jF = MLP([zi zj , TiC,jF ]), (7)

where [Â·, Â·] stands for the concatenation of vectors, and A and ACF can also be used for estimating the observed ITE as aforementioned in Eq. (1).

During the training process, data samples from the empirical factual distribution PË†F and the empirical counterfactual distribution PË†CF are fed into decoder g and optimized towards A and ACF , respectively. That is, for the two distributions,
the loss functions are as follows:

