Ablation Study on Losses For the ablative studies of LCF (Eq. (9)) and Ldisc (Eq. (10)), we show their effect by removing them from the integrated loss function (Eq. (11)). Table 8 shows the results of CFLP on CORA and CITESEER under different settings (Î± = 0, Î² = 0, Î± = Î² = 0, and original setting). We observe that CFLP in the original setting achieves the best performance. The performance drops signiï¬cantly when having Î± = 0, i.e., not using any counterfactual data during training. We note that having Î² = 0, i.e., not using the discrepancy loss, also lowers the performance. Therefore, both LCF and Ldisc are essential for improving the link prediction performance.
Ablation Study on Node Embedding XËœ As the node embedding XËœ is used in the early step of CFLP for ï¬nding the counterfactual links, the quality of XËœ may affect the later learning process. Therefore, we also evaluate CFLP with different state-of-the-art unsupervised graph representation learning methods: MVGRL (Hassani & Khasahmadi, 2020), DGI (Velickovic et al., 2019), and GRACE (Zhu et al., 2020). Table 9 shows the link prediction performance of CFLP (w/ JKNet) on CORA and CITESEER with different node embeddings. We observe that the choice of the method for learning XËœ does have an impact on the later learning process as well as the link prediction performance. Nevertheless, Table 9 shows CFLPâ€™s advantage can be consistently observed with different choices of methods for learning XËœ , as CFLP with XËœ learned from all three methods showed promising link prediction performance.
Sensitivity Analysis of Î± and Î² Figure 3 shows the AUC performance of CFLP on CORA with different combinations of Î± and Î². We observe that the performance is the poorest when Î± = Î² = 0 and gradually improves and gets stable as Î± and Î² increase, showing that CFLP is generally robust to the hyperparameters Î± and Î², and the optimal values are easy to locate.
Sensitivity Analysis of Î³ Figure 4 shows the Hits@20 and AUC performance on link prediction of CFLP (with JKNet) on CORA and CITESEER with different treatments and Î³pct. We observe that the performance is generally good when 10 â‰¤ Î³pct â‰¤ 20 and gradually get worse when the value of Î³pct is too small or too large, showing that CFLP is robust to Î³ and the optimal Î³ is easy to ï¬nd.

